\begin{abstract}
In frontline telemedicine the clinician who first inspects a suspicious skin lesion is usually a primary-care physician working from a photograph rather than a dermatologist with a dermatoscope, and what that clinician needs is a triage urgency rather than an exact diagnostic label. SkinRisk++ is built around this requirement. It maps the seven diagnostic categories of the HAM10000 dataset onto a five-stage ordinal severity scale, from normal to critical, and predicts that scale with a heterogeneous ensemble of three backbones: EfficientNet-B4, EfficientNet-B5, and an ImageNet-22K ConvNeXt-Base. Rather than appending patient metadata at the end of the pipeline, each backbone carries a dedicated metadata branch, so that age, biological sex, and lesion site interact with the image features before the voting stage. Training combines joint image--metadata Mixup, CutMix, and a class-weighted cross-entropy with label smoothing to handle a severe class imbalance. At inference the networks cast a soft vote with weights of 0.30, 0.30, and 0.40 chosen by an exhaustive 2-simplex sweep, and the same weights fuse the three class-activation maps into a single spatial explanation. On 1503 held-out images the ensemble attains a weighted F1 of 86.20\%, a macro area under the receiver operating characteristic curve of 97.11\%, and an accuracy of 85.36\%. The largest per-class gain is on stage 2 (actinic keratosis), where F1 rises by 18.7 percentage points over a two-model baseline, and expected calibration error falls from 0.052 to 0.007. An eight-component ablation and 1000-resample bootstrap confidence intervals confirm that each design choice contributes measurably, while a per-class sensitivity analysis identifies the residual melanoma-recall gap that bounds the system to an assistive role.

\keywords{Skin lesion classification, ordinal severity staging, convolutional ensemble, metadata fusion, model calibration}
\end{abstract}

