\section{Introduction}
\label{Int}

Melanoma incidence continues to rise across most demographic groups, which keeps skin cancer a major global health concern. The prognosis depends sharply on timing: five-year survival exceeds 98\% when melanoma is detected at stage 0 but falls below 25\% once distant metastases appear \cite{ref2}. Much of the gap between those two figures is, in practice, a referral-speed problem rather than a pure classification problem, and recent ensemble studies confirm that gains in early-stage accuracy translate into measurable mortality reductions \cite{ref1}.

In most healthcare systems the first observer of a suspicious mole is a primary-care physician, often working from a smartphone photograph rather than a dermatoscope. This creates a mismatch between what image classifiers output and what frontline clinicians need. Research models typically optimise for a precise diagnostic code such as \textit{actinic keratosis} or \textit{nevus}, whereas the clinician's first question is how soon the patient must be seen. Reframing the task as a five-stage ordinal scale resolves the output for triage and, in addition, exposes a hazard gradient that flat-class losses ignore: confusing a stage 0 lesion with stage 1 is comparatively harmless, but confusing stage 0 with stage 4 can be fatal. HAM10000 \cite{ref3} also ships structured fields --- patient age, sex, and lesion site --- that image-only pipelines discard, and they discard them precisely where they are most informative, at the rare and visually ambiguous classes.

Ensemble diversity is our third design lever. EfficientNet builds on compound-scaled $3\times3$ convolutions \cite{ref4}, whereas ConvNeXt uses $7\times7$ depthwise kernels with inverted bottlenecks \cite{ref5}; because these families read an image through different inductive biases, they make structurally different errors. In the standard variance decomposition for an averaged predictor \cite{ref6},
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:var}
\mathrm{Var}(\bar{y}) = \rho\,\sigma^{2} + \frac{1-\rho}{N}\,\sigma^{2},
\end{equation}
the dominant term scales with the inter-model correlation $\rho$. On our test set the B4 and ConvNeXt probabilities correlate at $\rho=0.64$, against $0.87$ between the two EfficientNets, so the benefit of adding a third model lives inside that correlation gap. Finally, because a black-box risk score is of little clinical use, we extend class-activation mapping \cite{ref7} across all three backbones and fuse the saliency maps with the same weights used in the probability vote, so that regions all three networks agree on are reinforced while single-network noise is averaged away.

The contributions of this work are:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item a clinically grounded five-stage ordinal re-labelling of HAM10000;
  \item a heterogeneous three-backbone ensemble with measurably low inter-model correlation ($\rho_{\mathrm{B4}\leftrightarrow\mathrm{Cnx}}=0.64$);
  \item per-backbone metadata branches trained with joint image--metadata Mixup interpolation;
  \item a three-model spatial-explanation framework driven by weight-matched saliency fusion; and
  \item a full 2-simplex weight search with bootstrap 95\% confidence intervals, an eight-component ablation, and an expected-calibration-error analysis, together with a per-class sensitivity/specificity characterisation of the residual error.
\end{enumerate}

