\section{Related work}
\label{Sec:Related}

Modern dermoscopy classification grew out of early convolutional networks that matched board-certified dermatologists on melanoma detection \cite{ref2}. A broad body of work has since explored convolutional architectures for skin-disease identification and prognosis \cite{ref8,ref9,ref10}, while the challenges organised by the International Skin Imaging Collaboration \cite{ref11} pushed the field toward harder taxonomies and demonstrated the effectiveness of ensemble strategies such as multi-scale pooling networks \cite{ref12}. Within that line, Qian et al. \cite{ref13} used multi-scale attention to sharpen lesion-boundary classification, and Annapoorani et al. \cite{ref14} combined tiered frameworks such as MSPLnet to advance medical image processing.

Clinical-metadata fusion is a parallel thread. Pacheco and Krohling \cite{ref15} reported a 1--2 percentage-point F1 gain on HAM10000 from simply concatenating patient demographics onto image features. Channel-guided multimodal fusion has since been applied to encephalitis prognosis \cite{ref16}, and genetic and lifestyle signals have been combined for skin-concern severity prediction \cite{ref17}. The structural change we introduce is the per-backbone metadata branch: instead of reshaping features through a single shared fusion layer, each model keeps its own calibration through a dedicated classifier head prior to the soft vote, which matters for the ensemble's downstream reliability.

Attention mechanisms and hybrid models are also widely used to handle complex morphology. Zaheer et al. \cite{ref18} augmented U-Nets with attention layers for prostate grading and explainability, and Lakshmi and Pushpa \cite{ref19} applied cross-attention fusion of ultrasound and clinical features. Severity grading in animals offers a close parallel to human dermoscopy: recent frameworks have classified and graded lumpy skin disease in cattle using attention-based convolutional networks and multi-task designs \cite{ref20,ref21,ref22}, confirming that ordinal-staging frameworks transfer across imaging domains.

On the architecture side, ConvNeXt \cite{ref5} modernises a ResNet with design choices drawn from the Swin Transformer \cite{ref23}, recovering the transformer-level accuracy of the original Vision Transformer \cite{ref24} on HAM10000-scale data without requiring the massive corpora those attention-based models typically demand. Ordinal severity grading on top of modern backbones has proven effective in adjacent medical domains, for example grading sarcopenia severity through model fusion \cite{ref25}. The literature consistently identifies architectural diversity and interpretability as prerequisites for deployable clinical systems; we adapt spatial mapping \cite{ref7} to the three-backbone setting to meet the interpretability requirement directly.

