\subsection{Training protocol}
All networks are trained with AdamW \cite{ref26} and layer-wise learning rates ($\eta_{\mathrm{backbone}}=10^{-5}$, $\eta_{\mathrm{head}}=3\times10^{-4}$), weight decay $10^{-4}$, gradient clipping $\lVert\mathbf{g}\rVert_{2}\le1.0$, and a CosineAnnealingWarmRestarts schedule ($T_{0}=15$, $T_{\mathrm{mult}}=2$, $\eta_{\min}=10^{-7}$). Optimisation runs for up to 60 epochs at a batch size of 32 under automatic mixed precision. Each backbone is frozen for the first few epochs (five for the EfficientNets, two for ConvNeXt) while the classifier head stabilises, after which the backbone is progressively unfrozen. The label-smoothed target for the true class $k$ is
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:smooth}
\tilde{y}_{c}=
\begin{cases}
(1-\epsilon)+\epsilon/C, & c=k\\[2pt]
\epsilon/C, & c\neq k
\end{cases}
\qquad \epsilon=0.1,\; C=5,
\end{equation}
and the batch loss applies an inverse-frequency weight $w_{k(n)}$, clipped at 10.0 to prevent the rarest class from producing runaway gradients,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:loss}
\mathcal{L} = -\frac{1}{B}\sum_{n=1}^{B} w_{k(n)}\sum_{c=0}^{C-1}
\tilde{y}^{(n)}_{c}\log p^{(n)}_{c}.
\end{equation}
For a sampled Mixup pair \cite{ref27} with $\lambda\sim\mathrm{Beta}(0.3,0.3)$ we interpolate both the image and the metadata,
\begin{align}
\label{eq:mixupimg}
\tilde{\mathbf{X}} &= \lambda\mathbf{X}_{a}+(1-\lambda)\mathbf{X}_{b},\\
\label{eq:mixupmeta}
\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{\mathrm{meta}} &= \lambda\mathbf{x}^{(a)}_{\mathrm{meta}}
+(1-\lambda)\mathbf{x}^{(b)}_{\mathrm{meta}}.
\end{align}
CutMix \cite{ref28} leaves the metadata untouched, since pasting an image patch does not change a patient's age or lesion site. Each batch draws Mixup with probability 0.20, CutMix with probability 0.20, and otherwise passes through unaltered.

\subsection{Ensemble aggregation and clinical score}
The ensemble posterior is a weighted sum of the three softmax vectors,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:vote}
\hat{\mathbf{p}} = w_{\mathrm{B4}}\mathbf{p}^{(\mathrm{B4})}
+ w_{\mathrm{B5}}\mathbf{p}^{(\mathrm{B5})}
+ w_{\mathrm{Cnx}}\mathbf{p}^{(\mathrm{Cnx})},
\qquad \textstyle\sum_{k}w_{k}=1,\; w_{k}\ge0.
\end{equation}
We swept the 2-simplex at a step of 0.05, evaluating 231 weight triples; the argmax of validation F1 fell at (0.30, 0.30, 0.40), and the surrounding F1 surface is a broad plateau rather than a fragile peak, so the operating point is robust to small retuning. The posterior is reduced to a scalar risk score by taking the index-weighted sum,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:risk}
R(x) = 25\sum_{c=0}^{4} s_{c}\,\hat{p}_{c}(x), \qquad s_{c}\in\{0,1,2,3,4\},
\end{equation}
giving a 0--100 scale with triage cutoffs at $R\in\{20,40,60,80\}$.

\subsection{Fused spatial interpretability}
Let $\mathbf{A}^{(k)}$ denote the final convolutional activations of backbone $k$ and $h^{(k)}_{t}$ the target logit. We compute the channel-importance weights $\alpha^{(k,t)}_{j}=\frac{1}{H_{k}W_{k}}\sum_{u,v}\partial h^{(k)}_{t}/\partial A^{(k)}_{j,u,v}$ and form the per-backbone saliency map $\mathbf{L}^{(k,t)}=\mathrm{ReLU}(\sum_{j}\alpha^{(k,t)}_{j}\mathbf{A}^{(k)}_{j})$, min--max normalised to $[0,1]$. Because the three backbones operate at different resolutions, each map is bilinearly resized to a common dimension and the maps are blended with the probability-vote weights,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:fuse}
\mathbf{L}^{\star} = \mathcal{N}\!\left(w_{\mathrm{B4}}\tilde{\mathbf{L}}^{
(\mathrm{B4})}+w_{\mathrm{B5}}\tilde{\mathbf{L}}^{(\mathrm{B5})}
+w_{\mathrm{Cnx}}\tilde{\mathbf{L}}^{(\mathrm{Cnx})}\right),
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{N}(\cdot)$ is min--max normalisation. Equation~\ref{eq:fuse} is the spatial counterpart of Eq.~\ref{eq:vote}: regions of agreement are reinforced while isolated single-network activations fade into the background.

