\section{Results and discussion}
\label{Sec:Results}

All experiments ran on a workstation with an NVIDIA RTX~4500 Ada (24~GB VRAM) and 64~GB of memory, under PyTorch~2.5.1 and CUDA~12.1. End-to-end training of the ensemble took approximately 12.7 GPU-hours. We report weighted F1, one-versus-rest macro AUC-ROC, accuracy, per-class metrics, and expected calibration error \cite{ref29} computed over ten bins.

\subsection{Aggregate performance}
EfficientNet-B4 reaches 79.86\% F1 and B5 reaches 82.73\%, while ConvNeXt is the strongest single model at 87.94\% F1 on validation, a margin most plausibly attributable to its ImageNet-22K pretraining (Table~\ref{tab:aggregate}). Combining only the two EfficientNets drops F1 below B5 alone (81.55\%), the textbook signature of over-correlated ensemble members and the observation that motivated adding a structurally different backbone. With ConvNeXt included, SkinRisk++ reaches 86.20\% F1, 97.11\% macro AUC, and 85.36\% accuracy on the held-out test set. The F1 gain over the two-model baseline (+4.65 pp) exceeds the AUC gain (+1.79 pp), which indicates that the third backbone flips the arg max on borderline samples rather than merely re-ordering probabilities.

