\subsection{Statistical significance and calibration}
Bootstrap 95\% confidence intervals from 1000 test-set resamples place the SkinRisk++ F1 interval at $[84.77,87.63]$, fully disjoint from the baseline interval of $[79.75,83.35]$; the separation is roughly $2.9\sigma$ under bootstrap noise, so the improvement exceeds resampling variance, and AUC behaves the same way. On calibration, voting across structurally dissimilar backbones cancels much of the per-model over-confidence (Figure~\ref{fig:diversity}): expected calibration error falls from 0.052 for the best single backbone to 0.007 for the full ensemble, an approximately seven-fold reduction that yields markedly more reliable probability outputs.

