\subsection{Per-class improvements}
Every class improves over the baseline, but the magnitude is uneven (Table~\ref{tab:perclass}). Stage 2 gains +18.7 pp of F1, roughly four times the next-largest class gain. This is clinically meaningful rather than cosmetic: stage 2 is actinic keratosis, the rarest class and the stage at which early detection most directly prevents progression to squamous cell carcinoma. Because actinic keratosis is visually similar to both stage 1 and stage 3 lesions, dermoscopy alone separates them poorly; routing patient metadata into the feature branches lets the model use demographics as a tiebreaker, which is why removing the metadata branch costs stage 2 nearly 8 pp against an average of about 1.8 pp elsewhere.

