\subsection{Clinical diagnostic metrics}
A triage tool is judged clinically on sensitivity (the fraction of genuine cases a tier catches) and specificity (how rarely it raises a false alarm), both computable directly from the confusion matrix. Figure~\ref{fig:sensspec} reports them per stage. The ensemble is highly specific across every tier, reaching 99.1\% specificity on stage 4: when it raises a melanoma-level alarm, that alarm is almost always warranted, which preserves scarce specialist capacity. The critical caveat is stage 4 sensitivity of only 53.9\%. The system fails to assign the highest tier to roughly half of true melanomas, with most of those cases mapped to lower tiers, so high stage 4 specificity must not be read as clinical safety. In a triage setting a missed melanoma is far costlier than a false alarm, and this recall gap is the principal reason the present system is positioned as a clinician-assist tool rather than an autonomous one.

