\subsection{Error structure}
The confusion matrix and its ordinal-distance profile (Figure~\ref{fig:confusion}) show that errors are largely, though not entirely, ordinal. Of the 219 test-set errors, about 32\% are adjacent-stage slips ($|i-j|=1$) and a further 32\% lie at distance 2, so roughly two-thirds remain within two stages of the truth. The remaining tail is the clinically important part: distance-4 errors account for 23.7\% of all mistakes, driven chiefly by 45 true melanomas predicted as Normal. These distance-4 transpositions are precisely the failures a triage tool must minimise, and reducing them is the central target for future work.

