\section{Conclusion}
\label{Sec:Conclusion}

SkinRisk++ reframes skin-lesion classification as an ordinal severity-staging problem and attacks it with a heterogeneous ensemble of an ImageNet-22K ConvNeXt and two EfficientNets, each granted a private metadata branch. The system reaches 86.20\% weighted F1 and 97.11\% macro AUC on the held-out split, with most of the clinical weight of the improvement concentrated on stage 2 (+18.7 pp). The gain flows through three compounding mechanisms: the inter-model correlation dropping from 0.87 to 0.64 when ConvNeXt is added, the metadata branch sharpening decisions on visually ambiguous classes, and the progressive unfreeze schedule preserving pretrained filters. The fused class-activation framework lifts the ensemble's variance-reduction property from the probability vector to the spatial explanation. The residual melanoma-recall gap, however, keeps the system in an assistive role; closing it through uncertainty-aware ensembling and validating across diverse skin tones and multi-centre clinical settings  are the priorities for future work.

